But when Preston Cook searched high and low for any official documentation cementing the birdâ€™s status, he found nothing. Where did we get syphilis? In a study published Wednesday in the journalÂ Nature, an international team studied ancient DNA harvested from lesion-ridden bones or teeth of five people who lived in Peru, Chile, Argentina and Mexico either before or around the time of Columbus. They found that early versions of the microbe,Â Treponema pallidum,Â that causes syphilis and related diseases were already diverse and widespread. Their analysis suggests that syphilis emerged in the Americas within the last 8,000 years and spread across the globe fueled by European colonization. â€œThe syphilis debate was a big one, and it was a very emotional one ... a famous paleopathologist described it as one of the most enigmatic questions in science,â€ said Kirsten Bos, group leader for molecular paleopathology at the Max Planck Institute for Evolutionary Anthropology and one of the leaders of the work. She argued the new evidence would settle the matter. â€œItâ€™s a very clear slam dunk: Okay, this clearly came from the Americas.â€ Several outside researchers agreed the study provides valuable new evidence strongly suggesting an American origin for syphilis, but added that it wouldnâ€™t close the debate. Understanding the differences between the subspecies that cause these different, but related, diseases is a key question for scientists trying to understand these diseases today. FTC MAKES sellers REVEAL â€œjunk fees" The Federal Trade Commission on Tuesday issued long-awaited rules requiring companies to display the full price of a hotel room, concert ticket or sporting event up front to customers, rather than hiding any extra charges â€” often called â€œjunk feesâ€ â€” until the very end of the checkout process.The new regulations, which are slated to take effect next year, seek to crack down on â€œbait and switchâ€ pricing practices, according to FTC Chair Lina Khan, who said the agency has received a groundswell of complaints about service charges, amenity fees and a raft of other potentially obscure, last-minute additions to consumersâ€™ bills. The FTCâ€™s rules still allow companies to impose fees, so long as they are clearly displayed.The agency also focused its prohibition on just the lodging and live-event industries, not the fuller array of firms â€” from airlines to internet giants â€” that have similarly stoked public anger.

Young adults are far more likely to approve of Luigi Mangione. The pollster YouGov askedÂ a battery of questionsÂ recently about the killing of UnitedHealthcare chief executive Brian Thompson in Manhattan two weeks ago and the man who has been charged for it, Luigi Mangione. (Mangione wasÂ charged Tuesday with murder and terrorism.) Many people appeared unfamiliar with the story, offering no opinions. But among those who did, lots of young adults appeared sympathetic toward the alleged killer. And notably, they perceived those around them as sharing such views. The poll, which surveyed more than 1,000 people, showed Americans adults under 30 are about evenly split on whether they view Mangione favorably or unfavorably. About one-third hold each view. Adults aged 30 to 44 leaned only slightly negatively toward him. (In contrast, Americans aged 65-plus viewed Mangione unfavorably by about a 15-to-1 margin. Overall, Americans viewed Mangione more than 2-to-1 negatively.) Younger adults actually viewed Mangione more favorably than the man he allegedly killed, Thompson. Caption from article by Aaron Blake.

Reality TV contestants may soon be employees. The National Labor Relations Board said this week that contestants on the show â€œLove Is Blindâ€ are employees and should have the work protections that come with that classification. Once remedied, the caseÂ could become the basis for the improved working conditions that reality show stars have long awaited. After the agency worked with two â€œLove Is Blindâ€ stars who filed unfair labor practice chargesÂ in 2023, the NLRB regional office in Minnesota assigned to the case issued a filing Wednesday. It said the hit Netflix showâ€™s production companies â€” Delirium TV and Kinetic Content â€” had misclassified contestants as â€œnon-employee â€˜participantsâ€™â€ and found that they had required cast mates to sign participant agreements to discourage them from participating in legally protected labor actions, such as unionizing. The production companies and their former employees must come to an agreement on remedies due to the unlawful portions of the contract or meet for a hearing before an NLRB judge on April 22. Caption from original article by Samantha Chery.

The volcanic activity fills the skies with sulfur dioxide and is constantly changing features on the ground. Itâ€™s the most volcanically active world in our solar neighborhood, and has an impressive rÃ©sumÃ© for a place that is only slightly larger than our own moon.â€œIo is one of the most intriguing objects in the whole solar system,â€ said Scott Bolton, a director at the Southwest Research Institute. â€œThis body is completely covered with volcanoes over both poles, all across its middle, constantly going off. So how does this really happen?â€ Ioâ€™s volcanic origins have baffled scientists. Many thought a global magma ocean may be percolating under Ioâ€™s surface, a feature that could have been common in the early evolution of planetary bodies in our universe and could explain the wide spread of volcanic activity.

together they had two children son Matthew and daughter Alexandra Christopher is busier and busier doing Superman's 1 2 3 and 4 in 1987 Gae and Christopher decide to separate he moves back to the US and he sees his children on holidays later that same year Christopher meets a young singer actress named Dana Morosini they were a couple living together but again Christopher had commitment issues Christopher was Superman he was 6â€™4 buff athletic very physical he was a pilot he wind surfed sailed boats he learned how to ride horses for a project he was in even though he was allergic after about five years Christopher finally decided to propose to Dana and they got married in 1992 later that same year they had a son they named William in this documentary they talk about the tragic accident that happened in 1995 he was competing at a horse show when right before the third jump his horse just refused completely stopped Christopher was thrown off the horse fell directly on his head broken snapped just like a noose half an inch to the left he would have been gone half an inch to the right he would have just gotten up his first and second vertebrae completely destroyed his voice_to_text: in my last video I said that it was hard for me to get into Drake because he keeps bringing up random people and places that I would never give a fuck about and I got so many comments that were like â€œyou're just nitpicking Drake literally every other artist does that.â€ and I didn't really think that was true so I did what any normal human being who's unemployed and has an infinite amount of free time would do and I listened to four albums and wrote down every single time they mentioned either a person or a place first of all this is probably gonna be a long video so I'm gonna leave a time stamp here if you just wanna skip ahead and find out if Drake really does do this more than other rappers okay so the four albums I listened to were Chromakopia GNX Donda and For All The Dogs you might be wondering why Donda instead of one of the vultures and that's just because the vultures suck and I didn't wanna listen to em I also divided every person and place into two categories ones that I recognized and were explained and ones that I didn't recognize or were redundant one last thing before we start I'm not counting repeats as long as they happen on the same song if Tyler says hey Jane 15 times that only counts once but if Drake mentions Miami one time on six different songs that's gonna count six times chromakopia has a shockingly low amount given that two songs on there are named after people I only counted 16 instances and out of those 16 only two of them were ones that I didn't recognize and they happen in the same line on Ratatata he has a line where he goes â€œthem boys went to Leuzinger i skated to Hamilton.â€ and I had to look that up it's just about high schools in LA obviously the average person isn't gonna know that so you know two for 16 is not bad and 16 in total that's that's really low compared to the ones we're gonna get to GNX and Donda both came out to 47 most of GNX's was talking about rappers like every feature on the album said their name at least once talking about all the members of TDE the people Kendrick calls out on whacked out murals that accounted for a majority of them and then with Donda it was mostly like biblical characters and stuff like that so I knew most of them for both albums G N X ended up with three out of 47 I didn't know and then Donda it was 5 out of 47 I didn't know both pretty good ratiosÂ  so far we have 16 47 and 47 add those all together it's 110 I want you to guess right now whether or not you think for all the dogs had over or under 110 I'm gonna assume you know since I'm asking you that it was over Drake had 153 instances of bringing up a random person or place on that album but what's even more absurd than that is that 64 of those were ones that I didn't know and I had to Google that's absurd let's look at the percentages on this and see how crazy it is comparatively two out of the 16 times Tyler mentioned a person or place on ChromakopiaÂ  I didn't know what he was talking about that's 12.5% for GNX it was three out of 47 that's 6% for Donda it was five out of 47 that's 11% for for all the dogs it was 64 out of 153 that is 42% of the time Drake mentions a Person or Place I didn't know what he was talking about that's absurd obviously it's gonna be lower for the OVO goons but for a regular person not knowing what Drake's talking about 42% of the time is crazy so yeah other rappers do it but nobody does it as much as Drake does
